placeAddress: 238 E 58th St Unit 4, New York, NY 10022
reviewText:
I recently had the pleasure of visiting Tabla a la Tabla and it was an absolute delight! From the moment I stepped in, I was greeted with warmth and hospitality. The ambiance was cozy, with charming decor that set the perfect tone for a relaxing meal.

Now, let's talk about the food – it was exceptional! The selection of cured meats and cheeses was outstanding, each bite bursting with flavor and expertly paired with complementary accompaniments. Every item on the platter was clearly sourced with care and attention to quality.

Not only was the charcuterie top-notch, but the service was also impeccable. Paula was knowledgeable about the products and provided excellent recommendations based on our preferences. Their passion for good food was evident in every interaction.

To top it all off, the presentation was exquisite. Each platter was beautifully arranged, making it almost too pretty to eat (but of course, we couldn't resist!). Whether you're a charcuterie aficionado or just looking for a memorable dining experience, Tabla a la Tabla is a must-visit.
Loved it! I don’t usually write reviews, but the charcuterie board was worth every penny! And it was pretty Instagrammable
Delicious boards, accomodating services and easy delivery. Super cute! can't wait to order more!
Great selection of meets and cheese.  Everything is fresh and looks good, a bit pricey.
Shop doesn’t exist. Trekked across the city in search of a great crepe, only to find no shop :( Found another great crepe around the corner at Honey Crepes 👏👏

Experience was mediocre, staff seemed either tired and ready to go home or just had poor customer service skills. My wife and I opted for the Baked Apple and Cheesecake flavors.

The ingredients used were not fresh, our strawberries and apples tasted stale. The thin slice of cheesecake was bland and the amount of ice cream given for the outrageous over charge is ridiculous. Overall for $37, I would definitely spend it else where next time around.
Outstanding crepes, and very nice guys inside. The spicy Moroccan chicken crepe had just enough spice, but the chicken was beautifully cooked with the onions inside. Can’t wait to go back.
I got a savory, ham & cheese crepe to go on a Saturday afternoon. It was quite good.
Delicious & full of flavor & the staff was super friendly! I highly recommend.
Strawberry Nutella was really good , Ozzy was very engaging while making my order, will be back soon

OMG yes, go here...I went today for the first time because my kid has a game that makes strawberry crepes and she said she wants to try a crepe lol....we got the Nuttella strawberry crepe and omg it was so heavenly....it was $15 and change with tax and a tip (a bit pricey) but you know what, you have to treat yourself sometimes.....either way it was worth it, it was absolutely delicious, no lack of strawberries, each bite had  fresh sweet strawberries and idk what the custard is the there but it was yummmmy, and there was a lil sprinkle of nuts inside that was just perfect.....they have other sweet flavors and I saw some savory ones too like a bacon and egg one and I believe a Philly one.....so I will be back to try out some of the others, but the Nuttella one was absolutely the perfect one to try the first time....it was really spot on, me and both my kiddos shared one.

reviewText: The food was SO good. The manager and staff was very polite and graceful. Their food is for indians, unlike bungalow and javitri that is oriented towards white people. The spice level was as required. Their food taste just like the food back in delhi.

placeName: West Bank Gourmet Deli in Battery Park
reviewText: Our regular store when we were in NYC. Super delicious wraps and dishes. Everyone is super nice and helps you. The pastrami ruben is particularly recommended. We'd love to come back to NYC, also because of this store :) Greetings from Germany.

Maybe we ordered the wrong things, but this place was only so so. Toast made both plates bland, which would have been ok if it weren’t so pricy. Home fries were really just roasted potatoes, decent but I liked those more crispy. We were a party of 2 but they automatically added gratuity. Oh! Caramel macchiato was truly 3/5 stars. Not terrible, just no wow factor. Service was great though! They were very kind.
This place is extremely overpriced. For some reason they take advantage of being the only deli around the immediate area. Do not give them any money, hopefully they’ll go out of business.

Rare and wonderful place for great variety of Belgian beer (~8 kinds on tap and many more in bottles/ cans), ~6 styles of mussels, plus hearty steak frites, etc. in a laidback atmosphere with attentive and friendly service.

Prices are not cheap, but an evening at BXL is like an evening in Europe without having to fly there!

Beers are about $14, 2 lbs of mussels cost $28. They have an all you can eat mussel special on Sunday and Monday that I have made a mental note to go back for sometime — Yum!

This time I had my mussels marinière style, with white wine and shallots, which was delicious and light. Upon request, they brought some delicious baguette to soak into the broth.

Last time I had the mussels grande-mère style with cream and bacon, which was equally delicious, but definitely more filling.

My partner had the steak frites, which was definitely a nice portion, and cooked to perfection.

We were tempted by the waffle for dessert, but just did not have the room, especially after a Duvel or two!

This place is truly a neighborhood gem. I highly recommend going and exploring the delights of Belgian food in this gentle and enjoyable atmosphere.
Good service, nice atmosphere and really good French food!
A stone's throw from the Barclay Center, excellent burgers. Everything is excellent. Several gluten-free options possible.

Top service and an amazing menu! We had a group of 4 and then 2 friends came and they gladly moved us to the best table in the house with no side eyeing 😌. The escargot was perfect, the chicken and French onion soup is to die for according to my friends who live here and dine here often. Such a treat and LOVED the decor!  Forgot to mention the super tasty cocktails and mocktails.

I ordered the Pasta Bolognese, and it was served with spaghetti. The bolognese itself did not seem to be cooked with soffritto, which is known as mirepoix in French cooking. Nor did it have any form of guanciale, pancetta or bacon, and there was very little meat in it which consisted of ground beef. Plus, the bolognese had more of a creamy flavor profile than a tomatoey one. It’s possible that the creaminess came from ricotta, which would be more tolerable for a lasagne, but that’s not what I ordered. There was not even a speck of parmigiano-reggiano, or pecorino detected. It also clearly was not cooked for multiple hours.
Moving to the pasta, bolognese is only supposed to be served with egg fresh pasta like tagliatelle or pappardelle. Even the dried version of mezzi rigatoni would have been an excellent choice. Spaghetti is too thin to capture the sauce of the bolognese, more so for the meat in which it was made with. Spaghetti is better suited for dishes such as pasta al pomodoro, cacio e pepe, or carbonara.
I was not expecting this dish to be one-hundred percent authentic, but if you have something classic like a bolognese on the menu, at least present it as if the sweet, neighborhood Nonna made it. Nonna is not proud, and every time an authentic, classic Italian dish is prepared incorrectly, a nonna loses her wings. This dish would disappoint not only all the nonne in the Emilia-Romagna region, but the entire continent of Europe. And should be reported to the Embassy of Bologna.
There are a few things I will give praise for. The pasta was cooked al dente, and while not heavy handed, I could tell the pasta water was salted. The dish, spaghetti and meatballs did not exist on the menu, at least to my knowledge. Plus, I admired that the serving of pasta was adequate and not an entire box piled in a mountain on my plate. Also, while others may not find it enjoyable, I appreciated the dim lighting. Not to mention, I was fond of how the tap water we were drinking came in green, glass bottles, that way I could at least pretend we were drinking S. Pellegrino. Molto bene!
Finally, I would like to state the following, Delaware River water > Hudson River water. And please learn how to properly pronounce the word Bolognese. Per favore e grazie!

placeAddress: 200 Liberty St Suite 106-A, New York, NY 10281
reviewText:
Incredible vibe, spacious layout, and a huge bar—Sixpoint Brewing at World Trade Center is the perfect spot to grab a drink and catch a game. With plenty of TVs, it was an ideal place to watch March Madness, and the staff was incredibly attentive, making the experience even better.

Now, the beers… stand out. The Leach Cobbler is an absolute must-try—get it before it’s gone! And The Crisp is a fantastic, refreshing lager that hits just right.

The wings were solid, but what truly sets this place apart is the immaculate vibes. Whether you’re here for the beer, the atmosphere, or both, you won’t be disappointed. Definitely a spot I’ll be coming back to!

placeName: Norwich Meadows Organic Farm - Tompkins Square
reviewText: Norwich Meadows is a certified organic mostly no-spray farm that comes to the GrowNYC  Tompkins Square Greenmarket on Sunday year round from 9am-4pm.  The farm is very popular with chefs from top restaurants such as Jean Georges and home cooks around NYC.  Norwich has green vegetables throughout the year and fruits including melons and berries in the summer.  There is an extensive vegetable variety more extensive and fresher than grocery stores including kale, collards, mustards, spinach, herbs, lettuce, beans, cauliflower, tomatoes, and melons.

placeName: Norwich Meadows Organic Farm - Abingdon Square
reviewText: Norwich Meadows is a certified organic NY farm coming to Abingdon Square Greenmarket (12th st, 8 av) on Saturdays from 8am-2pm, from mid-May through Thanksgiving.  The farm's  practices  are even more natural  than certified organic standards, and Norwich has many special varieties of very fresh vegetables including dark leafy greens.  The farm also sells to many of the top restaurants in NYC including Jean Georges and Union Square Hospitality Group restaurants to attest to the quality.  The staff are very friendly like the rest of the Greenmarket.

reviewText: Prospect Hill Orchards comes to the GrowNYC Tribeca Greenmarket 8am-2pm on Saturdays year round with fresh berries including blueberries, raspberries, and blackberries, many of which are no-spray in the summer as well as peaches and cherries. Prospect Hill also sells granola with organic oats, cider donuts and baked goods including a sugar-free apple hand pie and sugar-free oatmeal raisin cookie.

Nous nous sommes régalés dans cette ambiance digne d’un film…  Amazing !

Je recommande sans hésitation, nous avons été très très bien reçus.

placeAddress: 250 Park Ave S at 20th Street, New York City, NY 10003
reviewText: In all, amazing food!!! This included fantastic appetizers as spicy feta, tuna crudo; great rolls and labneh; duck with forbidden rice; excellent lunch prix fix; fantastic wine pairing - sommelier is awesome. Would have been a 5 rating if it weren't so pricey.

placeAddress: 60 Van Duzer St 60 Van Duzer St, 10301, Staten Island, New York, Staten Island, NY 10301-3226
reviewText: Ich bin nur zufällig in Staten Island auf das Craft House gestoßen. Der Besuch war es aber absolut werd. Sehr zuvorkommende Bedienung. Leckere Bierauswahl und gutes Essen. 👍🏼
Great little brewery in Williamsburg. Wide selection of beers and food was excellent. Great place to watch the game or hang out. Our server Maddie was fabulous.
